<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Happens During Lowering</h2>

  <p>
    As the plant grows, you periodically release string from the hook and lower the vine slightly. The stem is then guided along the row while the growing tip remains upright.
  </p>

  <p>
    This “lower and lean” method:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>keeps plants manageable</li>
    <li>improves airflow</li>
    <li>makes harvesting easier</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Smooth operation makes this process much easier over time.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where Most Gardeners Get Stuck</h2>

  <h3>Hooks That Slip or Jam</h3>
  <p>
    Poor-quality mechanisms make adjustments difficult.
  </p>

  <h3>Weak Overhead Support</h3>
  <p>
    The system is only as strong as what it’s attached to.
  </p>

  <h3>Inconsistent Lowering</h3>
  <p>
    Irregular adjustments lead to uneven plant growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Overcomplicating Setup</h3>
  <p>
    Simpler systems are easier to manage over time.
  </p>
</section>

